    "summary": "WIA2005 Algorithm Design and Analysis Lecture 3, delivered by Dr. Asmiza A. Sani in Semester 2, Session 2025/26, focuses on Sorting Algorithms, with Lecture 4 covering String Matching Algorithms, and references including \"Introduction to Algorithms, 3rd edition\" and \"Algorithm, 5th Edition\"; its learning objectives include understanding Bubble, Counting, Radix, Bucket, and Shell sort.",
    "source_indices": [0, 2]
  },
  {
    "summary": "Sorting algorithms are fundamental instructions used to arrange data, typically stored in arrays or lists, into a particular numerical or lexicographical order (increasing, non-decreasing, decreasing, or non-increasing) which is crucial for optimized searching, readable presentation, and various application needs.",
    "source_indices": [1, 3]
  },
  {
    "summary": "Sorting algorithms are classified based on properties such as In-place (arranges data without additional storage) vs. Not-In-Place (requires extra space), Stable (preserves original sequence for tuples) vs. Not Stable, Adaptive (leverages pre-sorted input) vs. Non-Adaptive, and Online (processes data incrementally) vs. Offline (requires all input beforehand).",
    "source_indices": [4, 5, 6, 7, 8]
  },
  {
    "summary": "Bubble sort is an inefficient \u0398(n\u00b2) algorithm that repeatedly swaps adjacent out-of-order elements, while Shell sort, a generalization of Insertion sort, compares distant elements and progressively reduces the gap, with a time complexity ranging from slightly worse than \u0398(n log n) to \u0398(n\u00b2).",
    "source_indices": [10, 14]
  },
  {
    "summary": "Counting sort, Radix sort, and Bucket sort are non-comparative algorithms: Counting sort sorts elements based on numeric keys within a specific range (\u0398(n+k)), Radix sort groups keys by individual digits using a stable sort (\u0398(d(n+k))), and Bucket sort distributes elements into buckets for sorting, assuming a uniform distribution of input numbers in the range [0,1), achieving \u0398(n) complexity.",
    "source_indices": [11, 12, 13]
  },
  {
    "summary": "Selecting the most appropriate sorting algorithm depends on the characteristics of the input data, with Insertion Sort being suitable for nearly sorted data, Merge Sort or Heap Sort for completely reverse ordered data, Counting Sort or Stable Sorts for data with many repeated values, and Quick Sort and Merge Sort for random unsorted integers within a wide range.",
    "source_indices": [9, 15, 16, 17, 18]
  }
]
